@article{lee_highly_2022,
	title = {Highly Multiplexed Single-ended Readout for Continuous Depth-of-interaction Encoding {PET} Detector},
	volume = {63},
	rights = {© 2022},
	issn = {0161-5505, 2159-662X},
	url = {https://jnm.snmjournals.org/content/63/supplement_2/3317},
	abstract = {3317
Introduction: Our group previously developed a {PET} system using a single-ended continuous depth-of-interaction ({cDOI}) estimation method based on a single-layer pixelated crystal array optically coupled to digital {SiPM} and triangular teeth-shaped reflector strips (Phys Med Biol 2017;465-483). However, the lack of commercially available digital {SiPMs} has led us to investigate a multiplexing scheme for {cDOI} detector modules based on analog {SiPM} arrays. The multiplexing scheme was developed to obtain 2-dimensional light dispersion information while allowing a remarkably high channel reduction ratio.
Methods: The {SiPM} readout circuit was designed to instantaneously compute the first and second momentums of the light dispersion. A modified symmetric charge division ({SCD}) network was constructed by feeding the symmetrically divided output current from each {SiPM} anodes into a 1-dimensional charge division circuit (1D-{CDC}). Each node voltage of 1D-{CDC} was then summed so that the output voltage is quadratically position-encoded. The injected charge distribution was analytically derived (2003 {IEEE} {NSS} 2003; 2169-2173) enabling {DOI} value to be encoded as a difference between x- and y- directional signal variations. {GATE} Monte Carlo simulation was used to evaluate the feasibility of the multiplexing scheme on the {cDOI} detector module. The contribution of the non-uniform gain distribution of the {SiPM} array was considered by randomly weighting 64 anode signals with Gaussian distribution (μ = 1, σ = 0 - 0.5). To determine the circuit parameter, we estimated {DOI} resolution while the {SCD} network resistor ({RL}) and 1D-{CDC} chain resistor ({RD}) values varied from 1 {kΩ} to 10 {kΩ} and 5 Ω to 100 Ω, respectively. To examine the detector performance dependence on crystal-to-{SiPM} coupling ratio and crystal aspect ratio, we tested various arrays of {LSO} crystals with different cross-sectional areas (2.0 × 2.0 mm2, 1.5 × 1.5 mm2, and 1.2 × 1.2 mm2) which correspond to crystal-to-channel multiplexing ratio of 24:1, 42.7:1, and 66.7:1. We conducted crystal identification by applying a density-based clustering method on 3D histogram of interaction positions obtained with continuously encoded {DOI}. A non-tagging {DOI} calibration method with head-on irradiation based on the encoded {DOI} histogram, which is more practical than commonly used side-tagging method, was applied.
Results: The designed circuit allowed the derivation of {DOI} information from the x- and y- directional light dispersion with only 6 readout channels. Increased gain variation resulted in the slight degradation of {DOI} resolution but still remained below 3 mm until the standard deviation of gain reached 0.5. The {DOI} resolution improved as the {RL}/{RD} ratio increased mainly because the high {RL}/{RD} ratio reduces leakage current and helps the 1D-{CDC} resistor chain to function properly as a linear voltage divider. The crystals were clearly resolved in flood maps with average k-parameters higher than 5.5 in all crystal dimensions. Average {DOI} resolution was degraded as the crystal-to-{SiPM} coupling ratio increased with fixed crystal length. In crystals with the same aspect ratio, smaller crystals provided better {DOI} performance. Average {DOI} resolution of 2.68 ± 0.37 mm {FWHM} was obtained with 2.0 × 2.0 × 20 mm3 crystals showing no degradation comparing to typical {SCD} method. The density-based clustering method allowed effective crystal pixel identification while rejecting unwanted background events. Non-tagging {DOI} calibration was successfully performed with good agreement with the side-tagging method thanks to the well-identified event clusters.
Conclusions: The multiplexing scheme based on a modified {SCD} network that allows encoding of second-order statistics of light dispersion and practically applicable {DOI} calibration method seems to be promising for continuous {DOI} estimation with only a small number of {SiPM} readout channels. The proposed method will be useful in reducing the complexity of the readout electronics for high-performance {DOI} {PET} systems.{\textless}img class="highwire-fragment fragment-image" alt="Figure" src="https://jnm.snmjournals.org/content/jnumed/63/supplement\_2/3317/F1.medium.gif" width="440" height="247"/{\textgreater}Download {figureOpen} in new {tabDownload} powerpoint},
